HOUSE BILL 730
C2 6lr1979
CF SB 415
By: Delegate Korman
Introduced and read first time: February 2, 2026
Assigned to: Economic Matters
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 6, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Business Regulation – Maryland Franchise Registration and Disclosure Law –
3 Alterations
4 (Franchise Reform Act)
5 FOR the purpose of altering the period of time within which the Securities Commissioner
6 in the Office of the Attorney General may exercise a power under certain provisions
7 of law governing the sale of franchises; requiring the Securities Commissioner to
8 require that a certain franchise registration exemption be indexed to inflation or
9 deflation based on a certain index; altering the period of time within which an action
10 for liability under a certain provision of law pertaining to franchise offers for sale
11 must be brought; prohibiting a franchisor and certain others from inhibiting the
12 right of franchisees to associate for certain purposes; providing that an action may
13 be brought against a certain franchisor under certain circumstances; establishing
14 the Maryland Franchise Disclosure Document Renewal Fast–Track Review Pilot
15 Program and generally relating to the Maryland Franchise Registration and
16 Disclosure Act.
17 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
18 Article – Business Regulation
19 Section 14–102, 14–202, 14–210, 14–214, 14–227, and 14–233
20 Annotated Code of Maryland
21 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
22 BY adding to
23 Article – Business Regulation
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0730*

2 HOUSE BILL 730
1 Section 14–219.1 and 14–233
2 Annotated Code of Maryland
3 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
4 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
5 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
6 Article – Business Regulation
7 14–102.
8 The General Assembly finds that:
9 (1) THE SALE OF BUSINESS OPPORTUNITIES IS A FIELD THROUGH
10 WHICH INDIVIDUALS USE THEIR IDEAS TO CREATE ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY;
11 (2) BUSINESSES ADD TREMENDOUS ECONOMIC VALUE AND DRIVE
12 INVESTMENT IN THE STATE THAT CREATES CRITICAL ECONOMIC GROWTH;
13 [(1)] (3) the sale of business opportunities is a field in which investment
14 problems and deceptive practices are common; and
15 [(2)] (4) this subtitle is needed to regulate this field adequately and
16 prevent these deceptive practices.
17 14–202.
18 (a) The General Assembly finds that:
19 (1) FRANCHISING HAS PLAYED A ROLE IN THE STATE’S ECONOMY BY
20 ENABLING RESIDENTS TO OPEN AND OPERATE BUSINESSES IN THE STATE UNDER
21 ESTABLISHED SYSTEMS AND BRANDS;
22 (2) the widespread sale of franchises [has], WHILE OFFERING
23 OPPORTUNITIES TO STATE RESIDENTS, ALSO INVOLVES COMPLEX AGREEMENTS
24 AND SUBSTANTIAL INVESTMENTS THAT CAN CREATE AND HAVE created many
25 investment and business [problems] RISKS FOR FRANCHISEES, FRANCHISORS, AND
26 SUBFRANCHISORS; and
27 [(2)] (3) franchisees [have suffered substantial] MAY SUFFER losses
28 when the [franchisor or its representative] FRANCHISEE has not BEEN given complete
29 AND ACCURATE information about:
30 (i) the NATURE OF THE franchisor–franchisee relationship;

HOUSE BILL 730 3
1 (ii) the TERMS AND OBLIGATIONS OF THE franchise agreement;
2 and
3 (iii) the business experience AND OPERATIONAL PRACTICES of the
4 franchisor or its representative.
5 (b) The intent of this subtitle is to:
6 (1) give each prospective franchisee necessary information about any
7 franchise offer;
8 (2) [prohibit the sale of franchises if the sale] PROMOTE HONESTY,
9 TRANSPARENCY, AND ACCOUNTABILITY, AND FAIR DEALING IN THE OFFER AND
10 SALE OF FRANCHISES;
11 (3) PREVENT PRACTICES THAT would [lead to] RESULT IN fraud or a
12 likelihood that the franchisor’s representations would not be fulfilled; [and]
13 [(3)] (4) protect the franchisor–franchisee relationship; AND
14 (5) SUPPORT THE CONTINUED GROWTH OF FRANCHISING AS A
15 BUSINESS MODEL IN THE STATE.
16 14–210.
17 (a) (1) Whenever the Commissioner finds that a person has violated or is about
18 to violate this subtitle or a regulation adopted or order passed under it, the Commissioner
19 may order the person to cease and desist from the further offer to sell or sale of the franchise
20 until the offer or sale complies with this subtitle.
21 (2) After passage of a cease and desist order, the alleged violator may
22 submit to the Commissioner a written request for a hearing.
23 (3) The hearing shall begin:
24 (i) within 15 business days after the Commissioner receives the
25 request for a hearing; or
26 (ii) at a later date, with the consent of the alleged violator.
27 (4) Unless there is a timely hearing, the cease and desist order is rescinded.
28 (b) (1) Whenever the Commissioner finds that a person has violated or is about
29 to violate this subtitle or a regulation adopted or order passed under it, the Commissioner
30 may sue in the circuit court to enjoin the violation or enforce this subtitle or the regulation
31 or order.

4 HOUSE BILL 730
1 (2) The court shall:
2 (i) determine if a violation of this subtitle has been or is about to be
3 committed; and
4 (ii) if so, pass any order the court considers necessary to prevent the
5 violation or remove the effects of the violation and prevent it from continuing or being
6 renewed in the future.
7 (3) The court may exercise all equitable powers necessary for this purpose,
8 including:
9 (i) injunction;
10 (ii) revocation, forfeiture, or suspension of the charter authority or
11 privileges of a business organization operating under the laws of the State;
12 (iii) dissolution of a corporation or association organized under the
13 laws of the State;
14 (iv) suspension or termination of the right of a corporation or
15 association organized under the laws of another state or country to do business in the State;
16 (v) restitution;
17 (vi) restraining order;
18 (vii) award of damages to be paid by a franchisor or subfranchisor to
19 a person injured by a violation of this subtitle; and
20 (viii) appointment of a receiver or conservator.
21 (4) The court may not require the Commissioner to post bond.
22 (c) The Commissioner may not exercise a power under this section more than [3]
23 5 years after the violation occurs.
24 14–214.
25 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this subtitle, a person must register the offer
26 of a franchise with the Commissioner before the person offers to sell, through
27 advertisement or otherwise, or sells the franchise in the State.
28 (b) The registration requirement of this section does not apply to:

HOUSE BILL 730 5
1 (1) a transaction by an executor, administrator, sheriff, receiver, trustee in
2 bankruptcy, guardian, or conservator;
3 (2) an offer to sell or sale of a franchise that is substantially similar to a
4 franchise already owned by the offeree or buyer; and
5 (3) any other transaction that the Commissioner exempts by regulation
6 because:
7 (i) the transaction is not within the purpose of this subtitle; and
8 (ii) the registration of the transaction is not necessary or appropriate
9 in the public interest or for the protection of investors.
10 (c) (1) The registration requirement of this section does not apply to the offer
11 to sell or sale of a franchise by a franchisee for the franchisee’s own account, or the offer to
12 sell or sale of the entire area franchise owned by a subfranchisor for the subfranchisor’s
13 own account.
14 (2) A sale is not effected by or through a franchisor merely because a
15 franchisor has a right to approve or disapprove a different franchisee.
16 (d) (1) The Commissioner may require by regulation that a franchisor or
17 subfranchisor who claims under subsection (b)(3) of this section to be exempt from the
18 registration requirements of this section:
19 (i) file with the Commissioner a notice of claim of exemption in the
20 form that the Commissioner requires; and
21 (ii) pay a fee of $250.
22 (2) The franchisor or subfranchisor shall sign and verify the notice of claim
23 of exemption.
24 (E) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL REQUIRE THE FRANCHISOR NET EQUITY
25 AMOUNTS SET FORTH IN THE FRANCHISE REGISTRATION EXEMPTION UNDER
26 COMAR 02.02.08.10D.1 TO ACCOUNT FOR INFLATION OR DEFLATION BASED ON
27 THE CONSUMER PRICE INDEX FOR ALL URBAN CONSUMERS BY THE U.S.
28 DEPARTMENT OF LABOR.
29 14–227.
30 (A) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY TO:
31 (1) A FRANCHISEE OR FRANCHISOR WHO IS A RESIDENT OF THE
32 STATE; OR

6 HOUSE BILL 730
1 (2) A FRANCHISED BUSINESS THAT OPERATES OR WILL BE OPERATED
2 IN THE STATE.
3 [(a)] (B) (1) A person who sells or grants a franchise is civilly liable to the
4 person who buys or is granted a franchise if the person who sells or grants a franchise offers
5 to sell or sells a franchise:
6 (i) without the offer of the franchise being registered under this
7 subtitle; or
8 (ii) by means of an untrue statement of a material fact or any
9 omission to state a material fact necessary in order to make the statements made, in light
10 of the circumstances under which they are made, not misleading, if the person who buys or
11 is granted a franchise does not know of the untruth or omission.
12 (2) In determining liability under this subsection, the person who sells or
13 grants a franchise has the burden of proving that the person who sells or grants a franchise
14 did not know and, in the exercise of reasonable care, could not have known of the untruth
15 or omission.
16 [(b)] (C) The person who buys or is granted a franchise may sue under this
17 section to recover damages sustained by the grant of the franchise.
18 [(c)] (D) A court may order the person who sells or grants a franchise to:
19 (1) rescind the franchise; and
20 (2) make restitution to the person who buys or is granted a franchise.
21 [(d)] (E) (1) Joint and several liability under this section extends to:
22 (i) each person who directly or indirectly controls a person liable
23 under this section;
24 (ii) each partner in a partnership liable under this section;
25 (iii) each principal officer or director of a corporation liable under this
26 section;
27 (iv) each other person that has a similar status or performs similar
28 functions as a person liable under this section; and
29 (v) each employee of a person liable under this section, if the
30 employee materially aids in the act or transaction that is a violation under this subtitle.

HOUSE BILL 730 7
1 (2) However, liability under this subsection does not extend to a person
2 who did not have knowledge of or reasonable grounds to believe in the existence of the facts
3 by which the liability is alleged to exist.
4 [(e)] (F) An action under this section must be brought within [3] THE EARLIER
5 OF:
6 (1) 5 4 years after the grant of the franchise; OR
7 (2) THE LATER OF:
8 (I) 3 YEARS AFTER THE GRANT OF THE FRANCHISE; OR
9 (II) 2 YEARS AFTER THE DATE OF THE INITIAL COMMENCEMENT
10 OF OPERATIONS OF THE FRANCHISE THE FRANCHISE OPENED TO THE PUBLIC.
11 14–233.
12 (A) ALL FRANCHISEES HAVE THE RIGHT TO JOIN A TRADE ASSOCIATION
13 CONSISTING OF OTHER FRANCHISEES OF THE SAME FRANCHISE AND TO
14 PARTICIPATE IN THE TRADE ASSOCIATION FOR ANY LAWFUL PURPOSE.
15 (B) A FRANCHISOR MAY NOT, DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY, THROUGH ANY
16 OFFICER, AGENT, OR EMPLOYEE:
17 (1) RESTRICT OR INHIBIT THE RIGHT OF A FRANCHISEE TO JOIN A
18 TRADE ASSOCIATION CONSISTING OF OTHER FRANCHISEES OF THE SAME
19 FRANCHISE; OR
20 (2) PROHIBIT THE RIGHT OF FREE ASSOCIATION AMONG
21 FRANCHISEES FOR ANY LAWFUL PURPOSE.
22 (B) (C) (1) A PERSON WHO VIOLATES SUBSECTION (A) (B) OF THIS
23 SECTION MAY BE SUED IN CIRCUIT COURT FOR:
24 (I) TEMPORARY OR PERMANENT INJUNCTIVE RELIEF;
25 (II) DAMAGES, IF ANY; AND
26 (III) COSTS OF THE SUIT, INCLUDING ANY REASONABLE
27 ATTORNEY’S FEES.
28 (2) THE INJUNCTIVE RELIEF MAY BE SOUGHT FROM THE CIRCUIT
29 COURT IN THE COUNTY WHERE THE INDIVIDUAL WHO IS ALLEGED TO BE IN

8 HOUSE BILL 730
1 VIOLATION OF SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION FRANCHISEE RESIDES OR THE
2 FRANCHISE AFFECTED BY THE VIOLATION CONDUCTS BUSINESS.
3 (3) WHEN SEEKING AN INJUNCTION UNDER THIS SECTION, THE
4 PLAINTIFF MAY NOT BE REQUIRED TO ALLEGE OR PROVE ACTUAL DAMAGES
5 SUFFERED TO OBTAIN INJUNCTIVE RELIEF.
6 (4) AN ACTION UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MUST BE BROUGHT WITHIN
7 THE EARLIER OF:
8 (I) 2 YEARS AFTER THE ALLEGED VIOLATION OCCURRED; OR
9 (II) 1 YEAR AFTER THE DISCOVERY BY THE PLAINTIFF OF THE
10 FACTS OF THE ALLEGED VIOLATION.
11 [14–233.] 14–234.
12 This subtitle is the Maryland Franchise Registration and Disclosure Law.
13 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
14 as follows:
15 Article – Business Regulation
16 14–219.1.
17 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “PROGRAM” MEANS THE MARYLAND FRANCHISE
18 DISCLOSURE DOCUMENT RENEWAL FAST–TRACK REVIEW PILOT PROGRAM.
19 (B) (1) THERE IS A MARYLAND FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENT
20 RENEWAL FAST–TRACK REVIEW PILOT PROGRAM.
21 (2) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL ADMINISTER THE PROGRAM.
22 (C) (1) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL ESTABLISH A STANDARD FOR THE
23 REVIEW AND APPROVAL OF INCOMPLETE FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS,
24 INCLUDING FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS THAT WERE NOT SUBMITTED FOR
25 PARTICIPATION IN THE PROGRAM.
26 (2) THE COMMISSIONER MAY USE A TECHNOLOGY SYSTEM TO ASSIST
27 THE REVIEW OF DOCUMENTS AS REQUIRED UNDER THIS SECTION.
28 (D) THE COMMISSIONER SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS
29 SECTION, INCLUDING REGULATIONS ESTABLISHING REQUIREMENTS AND

HOUSE BILL 730 9
1 PROCEDURES FOR THE SUBMISSION AND APPROVAL OF FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE
2 DOCUMENTS.
3 (E) ON OR BEFORE SEPTEMBER 30, 2031, THE COMMISSIONER SHALL, IN
4 ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, SUBMIT TO
5 THE SENATE FINANCE COMMITTEE AND THE HOUSE ECONOMIC MATTERS
6 COMMITTEE AND POST ON THE WEBSITE OF THE OFFICE OF THE ATTORNEY
7 GENERAL A REPORT THAT INCLUDES:
8 (1) THE NUMBER OF FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS
9 SUBMITTED BY FRANCHISORS UNDER THE PROGRAM;
10 (2) THE NUMBER OF FRANCHISORS THAT PARTICIPATED IN THE
11 PROGRAM;
12 (3) THE AMOUNT OF TIME REQUIRED TO ADMINISTER THE PROGRAM;
13 (3) (4) AN ANALYSIS OF WHETHER THERE WAS ANY IMPACT ON
14 FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS SUBMITTED OUTSIDE THE PROGRAM,
15 INCLUDING THE AMOUNT OF TIME REQUIRED FOR THE ANALYSIS OF FRANCHISE
16 DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS THAT WERE REJECTED;
17 (4) (5) A DESCRIPTION OF PROGRAMS IN OTHER STATES THAT
18 ADDRESS EXEMPTIONS FOR CERTAIN ESTABLISHED FRANCHISORS, INCLUDING THE
19 ELIGIBILITY STANDARDS BY WHICH THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITY MAKES
20 DETERMINATIONS REGARDING ESTABLISHED FRANCHISORS;
21 (5) (6) AN ANALYSIS OF WHETHER THE PROGRAM EFFECTS
22 CONSUMER PROTECTION, AND THE EXTENT TO WHICH, THE PROGRAM MAINTAINS
23 OR ENHANCES THE PROTECTIONS AFFORDED TO PROSPECTIVE FRANCHISEES
24 UNDER THE MARYLAND FRANCHISE REGISTRATION AND DISCLOSURE LAW,
25 INCLUDING:
26 (I) AN EVALUATION OF WHETHER THE EXPEDITED REVIEW OF
27 FRANCHISOR REGISTRATION APPLICATIONS UNDER THE PROGRAM DIMINISHES
28 THE EFFICACY OF THE DISCLOSURE REQUIREMENTS AND REVIEW STANDARDS; AND
29 (II) A DESCRIPTION OF ANY FRANCHISEE PROTECTION
30 BENEFITS THAT MAY RESULT FROM A MORE TIMELY AND EFFICIENT REGISTRATION
31 PROCESS; AND
32 (6) (7) INFORMATION REGARDING THE EFFICIENCY OF THE
33 REVIEW OF FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS SUBMITTED FOR PARTICIPATION
34 IN THE PROGRAM AND FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS THAT WERE NOT

10 HOUSE BILL 730
1 SUBMITTED FOR PARTICIPATION IN THE PROGRAM, INCLUDING INFORMATION
2 CONCERNING:
3 (I) COMMENTARY PERIODS;
4 (II) AMENDMENT PERIODS;
5 (III) THE TIME FOR COMPLETION OF SUBMISSION AND REVIEW
6 OF FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE DOCUMENTS;
7 (IV) THE NUMBER OF REVIEWERS; AND
8 (V) THE AVERAGE NUMBER OF FRANCHISE DISCLOSURE
9 DOCUMENTS SUBMITTED EACH YEAR.
10 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
11 October 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 6 years and, at
12 the end of September 30, 2032, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the
13 General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
